                  , and another
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-317-person2613">
                  ANN 
                  WASS
               <interp inst="t18320906-317-person2613" type="surname" value="WASS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-317-person2613" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-317-person2613" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live with my brother, Leonard Wass - we <placeName id="t18320906-317-crimeloc1793">keep a little chandler's shop</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18320906-317-crimeloc1793" type="placeName" value="keep a little chandler's shop"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18320906-317-crimeloc1793" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320906-317-off1791 t18320906-317-crimeloc1793"></join> in <placeName id="t18320906-317-crimeloc1794">Wentworth-street, Whitechapel</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18320906-317-crimeloc1794" type="placeName" value="Wentworth-street, Whitechapel"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18320906-317-crimeloc1794" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320906-317-off1791 t18320906-317-crimeloc1794"></join>. On Sunday night, the 14th of August, between eleven and twelve o'clock, the prisoners Manning and Rands came to the shop, and had some beef and bread; they staid and eat it, and began to make a noise - my brother put them out, saying he would not have a noise there; he then shut the shop-window, put the door too, and went out to get a pint of beer - I took the jar, with the copper money in it, and counted the money into it; it stood on the counter - I heard the shopdoor creak, looked up, and saw something like a shadow passing; a neighbour came in, and gave me information - I then found my jar and money gone; there was 6s. 6d. in pence and halfpence in it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-317-person2614">
                  ANN 
                  SHEEN
               <interp inst="t18320906-317-person2614" type="surname" value="SHEEN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-317-person2614" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-317-person2614" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a neighbour of Wass'. I saw all the three prisoners, and two more that night - they all came together; I only saw three come to the shop - I heard them making a noise, and Wass turned them out; he went down the street, after shutting up his shutters, and drawing the door after him; I saw Rands and Manning, a brother of Manning's, and Philip and another man who is absent, all standing in the gateway by Wass' door - two of them went into the shop, and the other three remained outside; Philip took the jar out, and gave it to the other man, who they call "Waggoner;" he was one of the five - I had been watching them for half an hour; I gave an alarm directly - Manning and Rands were taken by a Policeman, who came up; they were close to the door when Philip and the other man went in and took the jar; they had kept together for about half an hour before.</p>
               <p>Philip. Q. Did you see me - I was asleep, drunk, at a public-house at the time? A. I saw you.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-317-person2615">
                  HENRY 
                  BOLTON
               <interp inst="t18320906-317-person2615" type="surname" value="BOLTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-317-person2615" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-317-person2615" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Policeman. I received information from Sheen, and took Rands, who stood about the centre of the street, four or five yards from the prosecutor's door - he was in company with Manning.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-317-person2616">
                  WILLIAM 
                  STRAND
               <interp inst="t18320906-317-person2616" type="surname" value="STRAND"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-317-person2616" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-317-person2616" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Policeman. I heard the alarm, and took Manning four or five yards from the prosecutor's house; I had gone down the street ten minutes before, when two of the prisoners, and three or four more, were standing against the window, all in company.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-317-person2617">
                  HENRY 
                  COTTON
               <interp inst="t18320906-317-person2617" type="surname" value="COTTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-317-person2617" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-317-person2617" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Policeman. I apprehended Philip next day in Wentworth-street.</p>
               <p>Philip's Defence. I got rather tipsy, and went to a public-house, laid down, and went to sleep till about twelve o'clock - two young men came in, and raised me up to go and have a quartern of liquor at the bar, which I did - Mr. Wass came in for half a pint of beer, and when he went back his shop was robbed; I have subpoenaed a witness who was sitting by the side of Mrs. Sheen, and must have seen more of the robbery.</p>

               <p>Manning's Defence. I went to the shop and bought what I wanted; I went out, and two or three hundred yards from the shop, heard of the robbery - I went back, and they took me.</p>
               <p>Rand's Defence. I went and bought the bread and meat, and got about a hundred yards from the shop, I heard it was robbed, returned, and stood by my fellow prisoner; Mrs. Sheen came and gave charge of us.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-317-person2618">
                  ELIZABETH 
                  HALL
               <interp inst="t18320906-317-person2618" type="surname" value="HALL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-317-person2618" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-317-person2618" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . My husband is a carpenter; we live at No. 99, Wentworth-street, and keep the house. I was sitting by the side of Sheen; she said to me, "There is somebody has brought something out of Wass' shop, and given it to another man;" upon that, three men ran by - we both went to Wass' shop, and asked if she had lost any thing; she looked, and at last said she missed a jar with halfpence in it - we then came out; I sat down at their door, and Sheen said, "This is some of your concern, Mr. Manning," and they instantly came round Sheen; I had frequently seen Manning in the street up and down.</p>
               <p>PHILIP - <rs id="t18320906-317-verdict1795" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18320906-317-verdict1795" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 20.</p>
